    <Entry>
      <ID>31</ID>
      <DefaultText>Every character has 6 wearable equipment slots: Head, Chest, Gloves, Feet, and two [url=glossary:accessory]Accessory[/url] slots. Each item equipped in one of these slots benefits the character in several ways, including [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url], [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url], and bonuses to certain skills.

Equippable items fit into different broad categories: Cloth, Leather, Bronze, and Iron. Each of these provide different benefits. Some Talents require a character to have a certain type of item equipped before they will activate, such as requiring that a character wear only Light armor (Cloth or Leather).

In addition, characters have several Quick Item slots for consumables. These slots represent the food, potions, and other substances the character has at the top of their pack. These are the consumable items a character can use during combat. The Bandolier talent upgrades the number of Quick Item slots every character has access to.

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>32</ID>
      <DefaultText>Every character has two slots dedicated to wearing [url=glossary:accessory]Accessory[/url] items. These items are not visible on the character, but provide bonuses while equipped. Many Accessories are magical items that increase a character's Attributes, skills, or defenses.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>33</ID>
      <DefaultText>Food, potions, and other substances are all consumable items, meaning that they go away when they are used. Every character has several Quick Item slots that represent the consumables that can be used during combat.

Food items provide long-term benefits to the character who eats them, but they're not very strong.

Potions and herbs can be consumed for powerful bonuses that last for a short duration.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>34</ID>
      <DefaultText>Items in Tyranny have one of five [url=glossary:quality]Quality[/url] ratings: Common, Fine, Superior, Exquisite, and Masterwork. As an item's quality rating improves, so do its effects. Weapons deal more damage, [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] becomes more protective, etc. Item quality can be improved with the Forge upgrade.

Items of Common, Fine, and Superior [url=glossary:quality]Quality[/url] can be found on the bodies of enemies or in stores throughout Tyranny. Some locked chests will contain the occasional Exquisite item. The only way to obtain a Masterwork item is to improve it yourself.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>35</ID>
      <DefaultText>Every character has up to four [url=glossary:weapon sets]Weapon Sets[/url] they can swap between during combat. All characters start with two [url=glossary:weapon sets]Weapon Sets[/url] available. The Abundant Arms Talent allows all party members to access additional [url=glossary:weapon sets]Weapon Sets[/url].

Each Weapon Set requires a Primary Weapon. If that Primary Weapon is Two Handed (e.g. large swords or maces, a magic staff, or a bow), then no additional items can be added to the Weapon Set. If the Primary Weapon is One Handed (e.g. small swords, daggers, or thrown javelins) then a Secondary Item can be added to the Weapon Set (e.g. a shield or a second One Handed weapon).

Shields are Off-hand weapons, meaning they can only be equipped in the Secondary slot within a Weapon Set.

Characters can swap between [url=glossary:weapon sets]Weapon Sets[/url] during combat, but will incur a [url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url] Penalty for doing so.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>36</ID>
      <DefaultText>All attacks in Tyranny compare the attacker's [url=glossary:accuracy]Accuracy[/url] value to one of five defenses: [url=glossary:parry]Parry[/url] (direct melee attacks), [url=glossary:dodge]Dodge[/url] (direct ranged attacks), Endurance (body system attacks like Stun and [url=glossary:prone]Prone[/url]), Will (mental attacks), and Magic (attacks from spells and spell-like abilities).

[url=glossary:accuracy]Accuracy[/url] is defined primarily by the attacker's skill with that type of attack (weapon skills for physical attacks, magic skills for spell attacks, etc.). It can be influenced by [url=glossary:finesse]Finesse[/url], Talents, and other active effects such as spells or items.

When an attack is made, the attacker's [url=glossary:accuracy]Accuracy[/url] is compared to the appropriate defense on the target to determine how the attack roll will be modified. If [url=glossary:accuracy]Accuracy[/url] is above the target's defense, it will be more likely to result in a Hit or [url=glossary:crit]Crit[/url], less likely to result in a Graze or Miss.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>37</ID>
      <DefaultText>Afflictions are explicitly bundled sets of status effects that can be applied to, suspended, or fully removed from a character. While some afflictions have explicit overriding or exclusivity rules, most afflictions can co-exist with other afflictions.

When a spell is cast on a target, it and its subordinate effects and afflictions are all bundled together in a procedurally-bundled container created by the spell.

If these procedurally-bundled containers are applied while an identical version is in effect, the new version replaces the old.

No matter how many effects are on the target, generally only the best bonuses and the worst penalties are applied.

Some enemies can be immune to one or more afflictions. If so, these afflictions cannot be applied to those enemies.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>38</ID>
      <DefaultText>When an attack hits, armor is the primary means of reducing damage. [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] is usually derived from equipped items - primarily in the Chest and Helmet slots, though spells, Talents, and potions can increase a character's armor.

[url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] is subtracted directly from all incoming damage. E.g., an attack that initially does 20 damage to a target with 7 [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] would be reduced to 13. [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] can never reduce incoming damage below 1.

Note that many pieces of equipment will grant different [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] values against the different [url=glossary:damage types]Damage Types[/url].

Some types of attacks, such as Damage Over Time effects ([url=glossary:burning]Burning[/url], Poison, etc.) and weapon attack Procs are only reduced by 25% of the target's [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] value.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>39</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:armor penetration]Armor Penetration[/url] reduces the effectiveness of the target's armor by a specific amount. So when a target with 5 [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] is hit with an attack with [url=glossary:armor penetration]Armor Penetration[/url] 2, the target can only use 3 [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] to reduce the damage of the attack.

When a weapon lists [url=glossary:armor penetration]Armor Penetration[/url] among its information, this means that all attacks or abilities using that weapon will gain the benefit.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>40</ID>
      <DefaultText>Artifacts are powerful magical objects known throughout the world of Tyranny. They are the weapons and armor of ancient heroes, the scepters and insignia of Archons. Their magic is powered by their fame.

Equipping an Artifact will grant its wearer a powerful Ability that can be used in combat. As Artifacts are used to accomplish great deeds, their renown grows and so does the power of the Ability they grant. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>41</ID>
      <DefaultText>When a character is attacked and the hit result has been determined, the target's [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url] percentage is checked. [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url] can reduce an attack by one hit result (e.g. a Graze can convert to a Miss).

[url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url] is a property of equippable clothing and [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] and is also present in talents and abilities. Each modifier to a character's [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url] lists the type of hit result it converts, as well as the percentage chance it will do so when the character is struck. The types of [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url] are:

[url=glossary:crit]Crit[/url] to Hit [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url],
Hit to Graze [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url], and
Graze to Miss [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url]

The [url=glossary:finesse]Finesse[/url] Attribute increases the amount of [url=glossary:deflection]Deflection[/url] granted by equipped [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url].</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>42</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:breath]Breath[/url] is the attribute that determines how frequently Sirin can sing her Arias during combat. Each of Sirin's songs is broken into Stanzas. When a Stanza is complete, Sirin gains a single [url=glossary:breath]Breath[/url]. Each Aria requires a specific amount of [url=glossary:breath]Breath[/url] to activate. 

Sirin's accumulated [url=glossary:breath]Breath[/url] is lost at the end of combat.

The Quick [url=glossary:breath]Breath[/url] and Sustained [url=glossary:breath]Breath[/url] Talents allow Sirin to gain [url=glossary:breath]Breath[/url] at the start of combat, and carry [url=glossary:breath]Breath[/url] over between combat encounters.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>43</ID>
      <DefaultText>Companion Combos are powerful abilities that allow the Fatebinder and one of their Companions to work together in concert to achieve powerful effects in combat. These abilities can change the tide of battle and pull a victory from the jaws of defeat.

As reputation with Companions improves, new Combo Abilities will unlock.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>44</ID>
      <DefaultText>The frequency of using an Active Ability is governed by its Cooldown. When an Ability is activated, it enters a cooldown which can last from several seconds to multiple minutes or hours of game time. The [url=glossary:quickness]Quickness[/url] attribute reduces the length of ability cooldown timers.

Ability cooldown timers tick down while playing the game. They do not reduce when the game is paused or the party is traveling on the World Map.

Resting will refresh all Ability cooldown timers.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>45</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:engagement]Engagement[/url] occurs any time a character attacks an enemy with a melee weapon at close range. As soon as the attacker gets close enough, he or she will Engage. When a character is first Engaged, he or she will stop moving. The character is free to move again, but doing so provokes a Disengagement Attack. If characters break [url=glossary:engagement]Engagement[/url], they have a limited amount of time before the enemy they Disengaged can attempt to re-Engage.

Some afflictions make it impossible for a character to Engage an enemy. [url=glossary:paralyzed]Paralyzed[/url], [url=glossary:petrified]Petrified[/url], [url=glossary:prone]Prone[/url], and [url=glossary:stunned]Stunned[/url] all automatically drop [url=glossary:engagement]Engagement[/url] and can be used to get out of trouble.

Generally, a character can only Engage one other character in combat. Some Talents can increase this number, and some active Abilities can make it impossible for a character to be Engaged by anyone.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>46</ID>
      <DefaultText>Favor is one of two [url=glossary:reputation]Reputation[/url] alignments that determine how a given character or faction feels about the Fatebinder in Tyranny.

You improve Favor by aiding members of a Faction in combat, assisting them in completing Quests, and making choices that they approve of.

As your Favor with a Faction improves, new abilities unlock for your Fatebinder. These abilities can be seen on the [url=glossary:reputation]Reputation[/url] interface.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>47</ID>
      <DefaultText>Specific abilities can [url=glossary:interrupt]Interrupt[/url] their target, delaying their action for a short duration. When a character is Interrupted, they will play a reaction animation and go into [url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url]. When their [url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url] is completed, they will resume their queued action.

An ability that interrupts the target can have one of three strengths: Weak, Normal, and Strong. The duration of the target's recovery period increases with each [url=glossary:interrupt]Interrupt[/url] strength level.

An [url=glossary:interrupt]Interrupt[/url] applied to a character who is already in [url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url] from a previous [url=glossary:interrupt]Interrupt[/url] will have no effect.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>48</ID>
      <DefaultText>Magic in the world of Tyranny comes in two forms - the spell Sigils utilized by Mages, and the innate powers wielded by Archons. A talented mage can discover spell Sigils in the world and combine them together to create new spells.

Using spell Sigils requires a high [url=glossary:lore]Lore[/url] skill, with greater [url=glossary:lore]Lore[/url] required for more complicated spell combinations.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>49</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url] is the amount of time that a character spends between actions. Equipped [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] and Weapons have a large effect on [url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url], with heavier [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] and more damaging Weapons inflicting longer [url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url] times.

Certain Talents, spells, and potions can reduce a character's [url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url] time, though it can never be reduced below a character's base [url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url].

[url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url] is suspended when a character is moving.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>50</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:reputation]Reputation[/url] in Tyranny governs how major Factions and Characters - from Archons to Companions - feel about the Fatebinder. [url=glossary:reputation]Reputation[/url] is measured on two scales: Favor and Wrath.

[url=glossary:reputation]Reputation[/url] affects not only the quests you are offered and how characters treat you in the world. It also grants unique abilities to the Fatebinder. Different abilities are unlocked for Favor vs. Wrath, granting different rewards depending on how the Faction feels about you.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>51</ID>
      <DefaultText>Songs are powerful magical abilities wielded by Sirin, Archon of Song. When combat begins, Sirin will begin singing. Each of her Songs is broken into several Stanzas, with each Stanza applying a different magical effect or [url=glossary:affliction]Affliction[/url] to those around her.

Sirin is able to perform other actions while maintaining her Songs.

As Sirin's Songs are magical in nature, their power scales with the [url=glossary:wits]Wits[/url] attribute rather than with [url=glossary:might]Might[/url].</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>52</ID>
      <DefaultText>Each of Sirin's Songs is made up of several Stanzas. When each Stanza is sung, a magical effect or [url=glossary:affliction]Affliction[/url] is applied to those around Sirin.

Some Stanzas produce beneficial effects for Sirin's allies. Others are aggressive in nature and will damage enemies close to the Archon of Song.

Right-click on any of Sirin's Songs to see information about its Stanzas and what effects they produce.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>53</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] are powerful afflictions that last until a character rests. Each Wound reduces a character's maximum health and applies a penalty to their skill ranks.

[url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] can stack, adding their penalties together and making it hard for a character to continue through combat. When a character gains enough [url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url], the party should Rest and allow them to recover.

[url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] are gained when a character falls unconscious - when their [url=glossary:health]Health[/url] reaches zero during combat. On harder difficulty settings, [url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] are also acquired when a character's health falls too low.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>54</ID>
      <DefaultText>Wrath is one of two [url=glossary:reputation]Reputation[/url] alignments that determine how a given character or faction feels about the Fatebinder in Tyranny.

You gain Wrath by attacking members of a Faction in combat, forming alliances with their enemies, and making choices that they disapprove of.

As you increase Wrath with a Faction, new abilities unlock for your Fatebinder. These abilities can be seen on the [url=glossary:reputation]Reputation[/url] interface.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>55</ID>
      <DefaultText>Archon is the title given to people who wield immense power. It is also a title in [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' hierarchy (the rank immediately and distantly below the Overlord). In modern times every living Archon either swears fealty to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] or lives the nasty, brutish, and short life of a hunted animal. 

While all Archons possess magical powers, there is no other common thread between these women and men. An Archon might be made of fire, capable of conjuring storms, or able to heal with a touch - the only defining trait of an Archon is that this magic power originates from within. It is unclear how Archons come into their powers, but it is generally understood that most grow into or develop magical power throughout their lives, with only a few notable exceptions (such as Sirin, Archon of Song) having shown powers seemingly from birth.

Mages view Archons as the pioneers of magic, as any and all spells that 'mere mages' (that is, non-Archons) can cast all work by tapping into the power of an Archon that has come before - an act often referred to a signing a spell or invoking a sigil. For example, the Earthshaker Guild developed their earth-controlling spells from [url=glossary:cairn]Cairn[/url], Archon of Stone, while many of the Blood Chanter spells of frenzy and fear are adapted from the power of Sirin, Archon of Song. As there have been many Archons to wield similar powers (at least a half dozen Archons of Fire are known through history) it is possible that two mages might invoke different Archons to accomplish similar effects.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>56</ID>
      <DefaultText>Bronze weapons and armor have been the standard on Terratus for centuries. Only the most skilled smiths can reliably blend the correct ratio of copper, tin, and other materials to create a bronze alloy durable enough to withstand the rigors of combat.

Bronze weapons are lighter than the heavy iron produced by [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' [url=glossary:forge-bound]Forge-Bound[/url] mage-smiths. And, while bronze weapons can grow dull in prolonged battle, they do not shatter like iron weapons. A dull blade is better than one that splinters in your face!

Though copper can be found in many mines in the Tiers, the only reliable source of tin was from northern merchant caravans who traveled to the [url=glossary:bastard city]Bastard City[/url]. After [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' armies conquered that trading hub, the [url=glossary:younger realms]Younger Realms[/url] of the Tiers were left without the ability to forge new weapons and armor.

The trade requirements and the skill required to create a durable bronze alloy meant that only the wealthiest of Houses and nations could afford to fully armor their soldiers in bronze. This put their soldiers at a distinct disadvantage when faced with the fully iron-clad legions of the [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url].</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>57</ID>
      <DefaultText>The [url=glossary:forge-bound]Forge-Bound[/url] are mage-smiths sworn to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' service, though their operations in the Tiers are overseen by [url=glossary:tunon]Tunon[/url] and his court of Fatebinders. Each [url=glossary:forge-bound]Forge-Bound[/url] uses magic as a tool to augment their personal craft - most commonly smelting and metalworking but carpenters, tailors, and tanners are found in the ranks - and each mage strives to create that which is impossible with mundane hands.

Most notably, the [url=glossary:forge-bound]Forge-Bound[/url] are the sole masters of iron working in the known world. Using spells of fire resistance to wade into the forge fires, the [url=glossary:forge-bound]Forge-Bound[/url] can work iron at temperatures no other forge can match, and with a hands-on touch that no mundane smith could hope to achieve. Because of this vital skill, the [url=glossary:forge-bound]Forge-Bound[/url] are considered a strategic war asset - their lives regimented and controlled so that the forges may churn out iron arms and armor without debate, delay, or distraction.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>58</ID>
      <DefaultText>Creation of iron weapons and armor is the sole purview of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' [url=glossary:forge-bound]Forge-Bound[/url] mage-smiths. Only they have the knowledge and power to smelt iron ore and retrieve the valuable metal.

This secret of iron has enabled the Overlord to supply vast armies with iron weapons and armor. Where even the wealthiest of nations could only field bronze-clad armies of a few hundred soldiers, [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' forces number in the tens of thousands.

Unlike bronze weapons, iron arms do not require an alloy to create, making it possible to forge armaments from a single supply of iron ore. While iron is heavier than bronze and tends to shatter, the ease of replacing iron weapons makes them more desirable for [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' forces.

To maintain the advantage of numbers, the Overlord has decreed knowledge of how to smelt iron forbidden to all but the [url=glossary:forge-bound]Forge-Bound[/url]. Possession of this knowledge, or even possession of iron weapons and armor outside of the military, is punishable by death.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>59</ID>
      <DefaultText>Scribes trained by the School of Ink and Quill have long operated a network of carrier birds delivering message scrolls throughout the Tiers. This network was modeled after the one established in [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Empire by the Archon Talon.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>60</ID>
      <DefaultText>The standard form of currency in [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Empire is the copper ring. These thin loops of metal are carried on a rope, string, or leather cord worn about the waist or neck. Each ring is not solid - the ends may be pulled apart to remove a ring from the cord and used as payment.

There are three metals used in [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' ring currency: copper, bronze, and iron. 1 bronze ring is equal to the value of 100 copper rings. 1 iron ring is equal to the value of 100 bronze rings. Early in [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Empire, the weight and value of each ring was standardized. Counterfeiting rings in [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Empire is punishable by death.

As rings are used as currency, it is considered vulgar to wear rings as adornment or jewelry. Such decorations are seen as vulgar, and those who wear them are held in contempt.

The bronze used in currency is a weaker alloy than that found in bronze weapons and armor.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>61</ID>
      <DefaultText>For centuries the School of Tides was one of the most powerful groups of mages in the Tiers.  Tidecasters have spells that directly affect water, as well as spells that direct the push and pull of Terratus' moons, or that gather the rays of the moon Terratus Grave into searing light. 

Despite their arsenal magics, the School was long devoted to protecting sea traffic and fostering the arts. These actions made them a bit more tolerated than other mage schools in the Tiers - most notably in Haven, where the School had its once-great academy. 

Shortly before [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] troops came south, the School's founder - Occulted Jade, Archon of Tides, vanished across the ocean - fleeing [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' advance and taking most of her disciples with her across the sea - never to be heard from again.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>62</ID>
      <DefaultText>Though it wore the name of 'school' for hundreds of years, the School of Wild Wrath more resembled a mercenary outfit, with its elders more than eager to aim the School's destructive impulses at any foe for the right price. 

Having studied the many Archons of Fire over the ages (most notably Thousand Embers and the Sun Queen), the School's mages were concerned with little beyond conflict and battle - pursuits that made the School largely hated and reviled. 

The School of Wild Wrath met its end at the hands of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' armies in the first year of the war. Its elders now swear fealty to [url=glossary:the voices of nerat]the Voices of Nerat[/url] as the Blood Chanters Guild, and those not granted amnesty by Nerat were rounded up and executed by the [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url].</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>63</ID>
      <DefaultText>Sigil is the catch-all term for a symbol, rune, or glyph used to channel magic. Most often, a sigil is used to refer to the name of an Archon in this context. Spell casting works on the principle that Archons create new magical phenomena, and mages then imitate these powers - it is the Archon's sigil that a mage must invoke to channel that Archon's power.

Proper spell casting uses not only the core sigil (for example, a ball of fire would need to start with the sigil of the Archon of Fire) but sigils for shape (a 'bolt' sigil in the fireball example) and for various modifications. Skilled mages have been known to uses sigils that prolong, extend, echo, or intensify their spells.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>64</ID>
      <DefaultText>Every man, woman, and child on Terratus can point to the nearest Spire as it towers above the horizon. From the images and symbols engraved on the surface of each Spire, it is clear that these structures were created by man. No one now alive knows who created them, or what feats of magic allow them to rise so high into the air.

Spires are often found near or connected to the Oldwalls. As such, many cultures view them as signs of ill fortune.

Given their immense height, the Spires make excellent navigational aids for land and sea travel. Merchants will often trade directions that use Spires as guides rather than relying on maps or trails.

Many mages believe that their powers intensify when they are near a Spire.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>65</ID>
      <DefaultText>Endurance resists attacks on the internal physical systems of the character (e.g. poison, disease, stunned, etc.)

It is defined by the character's [url=glossary:resolve]Resolve[/url] and [url=glossary:might]Might[/url] attributes, but can also be influenced by equipped items, Talents, and effects from spells and potions.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>66</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Will defense opposes attacks that are mentally-based (e.g. Confusion). It is defined by a character's [url=glossary:resolve]Resolve[/url] and [url=glossary:wits]Wits[/url] attributes, and can be modified by equipped items, Talents, and effects from spells and potions.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>67</ID>
      <DefaultText>Magic defense allows characters to resist harmful effects from spells and attacks that deal Arcane damage. It is determined by a character's [url=glossary:resolve]Resolve[/url] and [url=glossary:vitality]Vitality[/url], and can be modified by equipped items, Talents, and effects from spells or potions.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>68</ID>
      <DefaultText>Physical defenses are used to resist direct weapon attacks. Melee attacks are defended against using the target's [url=glossary:parry]Parry[/url] skill, while Ranged attacks are defended using [url=glossary:dodge]Dodge[/url]. As these skills are used, they gain experience and improve their skill rank over time. [url=glossary:parry]Parry[/url] and [url=glossary:dodge]Dodge[/url] can be modified by shields, equipped armor, Talents, and other effects from spells or items.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>69</ID>
      <DefaultText>An Active talent is one which the player must choose to use. For example, a character who has Thrust must select the Thrust icon and select a target for the attack before it will launch.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>70</ID>
      <DefaultText>Passive Talent</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>71</ID>
      <DefaultText>A Passive talent is one that can be added to a character where the bonus is gained as soon as the Talent is acquired and does not need to be activated.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>72</ID>
      <DefaultText>Modal Talent (Battle Stances)</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>73</ID>
      <DefaultText>A Modal Talent is one that can be toggled on and off. Its effects occur continuously while it is active. Only one Modal Ability can be active at any given time.

Modal Talents can be found in the Battle Stances group in the HUD when a character is selected.

When a Modal Talent is deactivated, all Modal abilities go into recovery - no other Modals can be activated during this period. Moving will temporarily halt the recovery of Modal Abilities until your character stops moving.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>74</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:death]Death[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>75</ID>
      <DefaultText>On certain difficulty settings, if a character is reduced to 0 [url=glossary:health]Health[/url], they are killed. A dead character cannot be brought back.

A character must be at 0 [url=glossary:health]Health[/url] and be at the maximum number of [url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] for the current difficulty setting in order to be killed.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>76</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:health]Health[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>77</ID>
      <DefaultText>A character's [url=glossary:health]Health[/url] determines their survivability in combat. Damage that is not absorbed by a target's [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] goes straight to their [url=glossary:health]Health[/url]. Potions and healing spells can restore [url=glossary:health]Health[/url] in combat.

When a character's [url=glossary:health]Health[/url] reaches 0, they will be Knocked Out. A Knocked Out character can be brought back in combat through the use of Active Abilities. Otherwise, characters will regain [url=glossary:health]Health[/url] at the end of combat (assuming they're on the winning side).

Based on the game's difficulty setting, characters gain [url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] when they fall below a specific health threshold during combat, and will gain additional [url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] when they are Knocked Out.

Based on game settings, a character that reaches 0 health can be Killed.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>78</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:crit]Crit[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>79</ID>
      <DefaultText>A critical hit (or [url=glossary:crit]Crit[/url]) is a supremely successful attack, and will increase both damage dealt and extend the duration of any applied effects. Crits are more likely to occur when the attacker's [url=glossary:accuracy]Accuracy[/url] is significantly greater than the target's defense.

Any attack has a 5% minimum chance to [url=glossary:crit]Crit[/url].</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>80</ID>
      <DefaultText>Graze</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>81</ID>
      <DefaultText>A Graze is any attack that results in only a glancing blow on the target. Grazes deal less damage than a hit, and Afflictions and Interrupts do not apply to the target. Grazes are more likely to occur when the attacker's [url=glossary:accuracy]Accuracy[/url] is less than the target's defense.

Any attack has a minimum 10% chance to Graze.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>82</ID>
      <DefaultText>Miss</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>83</ID>
      <DefaultText>A miss occurs when an attack roll results in a low value. This typically occurs when the target's defense is significantly greater than the attacker's [url=glossary:accuracy]Accuracy[/url]. Though missed attacks don't deal damage or apply effects, characters still gain skill experience from their attacks.

Any attack has a minimum 5% chance to miss.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>84</ID>
      <DefaultText>Hit</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>85</ID>
      <DefaultText>A Hit results in the target taking standard damage and effects being applied for their standard duration.

Any attack has a minimum 5% chance to be a Hit.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>86</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:damage types]Damage Types[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>87</ID>
      <DefaultText>There are nine damage types in Tyranny: Slash, Pierce, Crush, Burn, Shock, Freeze, Arcane, Corrode, and Raw. Damage types are used to determine how easily a target resists damage of that type based on their [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url]. A creature or suit of armor may be very resistant to one type of damage but quite vulnerable to another.

Some weapons or attacks may do multiple damage types or list an "or" between their damage types. When an "or" is listed, the attack will always do the damage type that the target is most vulnerable to. Raw damage is the only damage type that ignores all Damage Reductions and is generally associated with poisons and similar effects.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>88</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:scouting]Scouting[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>89</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:scouting]Scouting[/url] mode is used for two purposes: sneaking and searching. Sneaking may allow you to avoid or gain a tactical advantage against difficult foes. Searching provides a bonus to detecting traps and hidden objects.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>90</ID>
      <DefaultText>Primary Defense</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>91</ID>
      <DefaultText>Some attacks check against multiple defenses. For example, the poison on a dagger. In this example, the dagger's swing is defended by the Primary Defense - in this case, [url=glossary:parry]Parry[/url]. Only if the Primary Defense is overcome will the poison try to apply, defended by a Secondary Defense.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>92</ID>
      <DefaultText>Secondary Defense</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>93</ID>
      <DefaultText>Secondary Defenses are used for second stage attacks, e.g. the poison on a dagger. In this example, the first attack (the dagger swing) targets one defense ([url=glossary:parry]Parry[/url]) and the poison's attack will only be checked if the first attack hits. If the attack hits, then the Secondary Defense (in this case, Endurance against Poison) is checked to determine the effects. If the initial attack misses, then the Secondary Defense will not be checked.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>94</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:camping supplies]Camping Supplies[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>95</ID>
      <DefaultText>Camping supplies are required to rest in most wilderness and dungeon areas. This represents a collection of items that would be required to make camp, prepare food, bind wounds, and otherwise rest and recuperate. Many stores sell camping supplies, but supplies can occasionally be found in containers or on enemies. The game's level of difficulty restricts the maximum number of camping supplies you can carry at once. Lower levels of difficulty allow you to carry a greater number.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>96</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:stash]Stash[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>97</ID>
      <DefaultText>The [url=glossary:stash]Stash[/url] holds all of the player's extra items that cannot fit into the inventory of individual characters. The [url=glossary:stash]Stash[/url] also holds special items like crafting supplies and quest items.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>98</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:hotkeys]Hotkeys[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>99</ID>
      <DefaultText>You can hotkey any ability by hovering the mouse cursor over its button and pressing the desired hotkey. The number keys (1 - 0) are automatically assigned to new abilities as they are learned.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>100</ID>
      <DefaultText>Causes Raw damage over time.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>101</ID>
      <DefaultText>Skill Rank</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>102</ID>
      <DefaultText>Each skill has a value that determines how proficient a character is in that skill. This value is called the skill's rank.

As a character uses a skill, they gain experience in that skill. When they gain enough experience, the skill increases in rank. Higher ranks in a skill increase the chance of an action resulting in a critical success, and can overcome higher defenses on enemies.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>103</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Blood Chanters are the [url=glossary:scarlet chorus]Scarlet Chorus[/url]' magical corps. Using fire magic stolen from the conquered School of Wild Wrath, and spells of fear and frenzy based on the study of Sirin, Archon of Song, the Blood Chanters practice a violent and visceral brand of magic.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>104</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:parry]Parry[/url] and [url=glossary:dodge]Dodge[/url] reduced by 50.  Removed when damaged.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>105</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:accuracy]Accuracy[/url] reduced by 30.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>106</ID>
      <DefaultText>Causes Burn damage over time.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>107</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:confused]Confused[/url] targets wander aimlessly.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>108</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:recovery]Recovery[/url] increased by 50%.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>109</ID>
