    <Entry>
      <ID>129</ID>
      <DefaultText>Calendar</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>130</ID>
      <DefaultText>The calendar of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Empire is divided into 14 Spans. Each Span is 26 days long and is divided into 5 weeks - called Fists - of 5 days each. The last day of the Span is [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Day, a day of rest.

The days of each Fist are named after roles that [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' considers important to the Empire: Warriors' Day, Healers' Day, Judges' Day, Farmers' Day, and Smiths' Day.

The years of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' calendar are counted from the day of the Overlord's First [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] and known as the True Reckoning (TR).

Dates are commonly referred to using the name of the day and the day of the Span. For example: Judges' Day, 18 Span of Blood. 

A less formal usage is to refer to the date by the order of its day in the span. For example: Second Judges' of Frostfall. 

More formal usages will specify the date using the Fist and the year. For example: Smiths' Day, in the Second Fist of the Span of Storms, 428 TR.

The 14 Spans of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Calendar are: Span of Forgefire, Span of Tempering, Span of Storms, Span of Swords, Span of Blood, Span of Conquest, Span of Rapax, Span of Siege, Span of Flames, Span of Reaping, Span of Ruin, Span of Feasting, Span of Shadow, and the Span of Frostfall.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>132</ID>
      <DefaultText>A character's [url=glossary:precision]Precision[/url] determines the chance that, when attacking a target and after the hit result is determined, the hit will be upgraded to a higher hit result (e.g. a Graze will be converted to a Hit).

[url=glossary:precision]Precision[/url] is granted by some glove items, and can also be granted by Talents. Bonuses to [url=glossary:precision]Precision[/url] either apply to all hit results, or only affect a single type of conversion (IE: Graze to Hit precision). There are three types of [url=glossary:precision]Precision[/url] conversion, listed below:

Miss [url=glossary:precision]Precision[/url] increases the chance to convert a Miss to a Graze.
Graze [url=glossary:precision]Precision[/url] increases the chance to convert a Graze to a Hit.
Hit [url=glossary:precision]Precision[/url] increases the chance to convert a Hit to a Critical.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>133</ID>
      <DefaultText>Blood Chanter</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>134</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:riposte]Riposte[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>135</ID>
      <DefaultText>The ability to [url=glossary:riposte]Riposte[/url] can be granted to some characters through Talents. A [url=glossary:riposte]Riposte[/url] is an instantaneous counter-attack that can occur after being missed by an enemy's melee attack. When a Talent grants the ability to [url=glossary:riposte]Riposte[/url], it will also include the chance for the [url=glossary:riposte]Riposte[/url] to occur.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>136</ID>
      <DefaultText>Rite of Savagery and Stone</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>137</ID>
      <DefaultText>A coming of age ritual practiced by the [url=glossary:stonestalker]Stonestalker[/url] tribe of Beastwomen in the [url=glossary:stone sea]Stone Sea[/url]. In order to earn its second name and place in the tribe, a broodcub must engage in a series of challenge fights. These fights are generally non-lethal, though accidents may happen.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>142</ID>
      <DefaultText>Rite of Blood</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>143</ID>
      <DefaultText>Among the [url=glossary:stonestalker]Stonestalker[/url] tribe of Beastwomen, the Rite of Blood is the ceremonial challenge whereby one Beast challenges the [url=glossary:prima]Prima[/url] for dominance. The challenger must defeat the [url=glossary:prima]Prima[/url] or be cast out of the tribe entirely. Depending on the viciousness of the challenger, a losing [url=glossary:prima]Prima[/url] may be killed outright, or exiled in disgrace.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>146</ID>
      <DefaultText>Azurelith</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>147</ID>
      <DefaultText>After [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] of Stone shattered the fertile plains of Azure, these purple-hued crystals began appearing among the rocky outcroppings of the [url=glossary:stone sea]Stone Sea[/url]. While connected to the rocks of the region, Azurelith glows with a faint light. The Earthshaker mages are studying this phenomenon, hoping to use whatever power lies within the crystals to enhance their magic.

The [url=glossary:stonestalker]Stonestalker[/url] tribe of Beastwomen call these crystals the 'Elder Teeth', believing them to be manifestations of their ancestors. Mystics of the tribe wear shards of Azurelith and crush some crystals into powder used to make an incandescent body paint to strengthen their magical attacks.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>148</ID>
      <DefaultText>Fire, Frost, Shock and Arcane [url=glossary:armor]Armor[/url] reduced by 5.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>149</ID>
      <DefaultText>The [url=glossary:bronze brotherhood]Bronze Brotherhood[/url] is a mercenary company from the Free Cities dotting the Tiers' southern coast. Many of these mercenary companies were employed by [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' agents and slaughtered during the war. The [url=glossary:bronze brotherhood]Bronze Brotherhood[/url] survived thanks to their relatively safe posting at [url=glossary:lethian's crossing]Lethian's Crossing[/url], where [url=glossary:the voices of nerat]the Voices of Nerat[/url] hired the company to help protect the town's forge operation.

Among the most trained and dedicated warriors of the Tiers, the [url=glossary:bronze brotherhood]Bronze Brotherhood[/url] have a reputation for ruthlessness and tenacity.  Aggression and decisive thinking are so highly prized by the Brotherhood that the violent, enigmatic Scourge is the group's mascot - a creature most decent folk consider the stuff of nightmares. The term "Brother" is used for mercenaries of both genders, as the company's title harkens back to the archaic notion of 'living as men' (in Tiers custom, this amounts to releasing all claims to lands) to better assure an employer that the Brotherhood won't covet the realms they're paid to protect.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>150</ID>
      <DefaultText>The [url=glossary:unbroken]Unbroken[/url] Legion was the proud and accomplished army of the Realm of Stalwart. Citing their victories as evidence of skill, they prided themselves on never facing defeat while fighting on home soil. After the [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] of Storms tore apart Stalwart and twisted it into the [url=glossary:blade grave]Blade Grave[/url], barely a twentieth of the [url=glossary:unbroken]Unbroken[/url]'s former strength survived to continue the war against [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' forces.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>151</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>152</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' most powerful magic is that of the [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] - commandments cast upon whole regions that can control and destroy man and nature alike. 

Once cast, an [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] can rain fire, wither crops, demoralize cities, usher in endless night, or do whatever it is that [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] envisioned. No known force, magical or mundane can stop an [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url], though each [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] is often worded to include some condition or contingency that will see its end. 

Some Edicts have been short lived, delivering days of wanton catastrophe. Just as many have lingered for centuries.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>153</ID>
      <DefaultText>Earthshaker</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>154</ID>
      <DefaultText>Earthshakers are the magical arm of the [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url] legion. Nominally loyal to [url=glossary:graven ashe]Graven Ashe[/url], the Earthshakers and their leader Radix truly served [url=glossary:cairn]Cairn[/url], Archon of Stone. It is from [url=glossary:cairn]Cairn[/url] that they derived their magical ability to shape and manipulate the rock and soil of Terratus.

When [url=glossary:cairn]Cairn[/url] rebelled against [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url], the Earthshakers remained with the [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url]. Their detractors say they only stayed because they couldn't locate their Archon to join him in rebellion. Regardless of the reason, their loyalty earned them [url=glossary:graven ashe]Graven Ashe[/url]'s protection after the Overlord issued an [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] to destroy the rebellious Archon.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>155</ID>
      <DefaultText>Iron Walker</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>156</ID>
      <DefaultText>Iron Walkers are the most deadly fighters of the [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url] legion, giant men and women clad from head to toe in thick iron armor.

An Iron Walker spends much of their time in the center of the phalanx, ready to reinforce their Stone Shield brethren if any enemies penetrate the shield wall. When the phalanx nears a valued enemy target, the Walker will order the shield wall to part, and they will emerge from protection to cut their way through the enemy and eliminate the threat.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>157</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stone Shield</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>158</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stone Shields are the largest group within the [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url] legion. Each soldier carries a large iron shield into battle, where the shields overlap to form an impenetrable iron wall. The [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url] say that enemies break on the shield wall like waves on stone - giving these soldiers their name.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>159</ID>
      <DefaultText>Crescent Runner</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>160</ID>
      <DefaultText>Crescent Runners are the mobile strike force of the [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url] legion. Lightly armored, a Crescent Runner's job is to circle the phalanx and harry the enemy with hurled javelin attacks. Their goal is to bait the enemy into pressing the attack, at which point the Crescent Runners retreat behind the Stone Shields - allowing the enemies to break against the shield wall.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>161</ID>
      <DefaultText>Oath Bound</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>162</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Oath Bound are a select group with the elite [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url] - men and women whose lives are bound together by magic.

Sent ahead of the main legion to scout territory and assassinate key enemy targets, each member of an Oath Bound Fist is life-linked to every other. When one dies, the remaining members absorb their fallen comrade's strength, making the last Oath Bound the hardest to take down.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>163</ID>
      <DefaultText>Scarlet Fury</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>164</ID>
      <DefaultText>The highly skilled 'special forces' of the [url=glossary:scarlet chorus]Scarlet Chorus[/url], Furies are trained to ignore pain and crippling wounds in order to achieve their goals.

Scarlet Furies use a spinning, acrobatic attack style incorporating dual wielded blades to confuse and disorient their foes.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>165</ID>
      <DefaultText>Horde</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>166</ID>
      <DefaultText>The unwashed, undisciplined, unskilled masses of the [url=glossary:scarlet chorus]Scarlet Chorus[/url] are known as the Horde. The only advantage these "soldiers" possess is their overwhelming numbers.

When the [url=glossary:scarlet chorus]Scarlet Chorus[/url] conquers a town or village, a ritual known as the 'culling' is held. Every able-bodied man, woman, and sometimes child, is forced to fight their families and neighbors to the death. Only those brutal enough to kill their loved ones will survive to join the Horde, where they're given a chance to earn a name, a weapon, and some semblance of a future.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>167</ID>
      <DefaultText>Blood Hound</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>168</ID>
      <DefaultText>Blood Hounds are apprentice mages who are unable to properly harness arcane energy through sigils. Instead they channel magic directly - a dangerous practice commonly called "the Bleed". This pure magical energy is deadly to both themselves and their enemies.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>169</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stalwart</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>170</ID>
      <DefaultText>The proud nation of Stalwart was one of the last to fall to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' armies during the years of conquest. The [url=glossary:unbroken]Unbroken[/url] Blades had never been defeated on their home soil until they faced the might of the [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url] legion.

Ruled by the Regents of Stalwart, the nation refused to surrender before the Overlord's might. In retaliation for their pride, [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] issued an [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] that wracked the land with eternal storms, transforming the mighty nation into a rust-choked ruin known as the [url=glossary:blade grave]Blade Grave[/url].</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>171</ID>
      <DefaultText>Apex</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>172</ID>
      <DefaultText>Apex was one of the [url=glossary:younger realms]Younger Realms[/url], the four nations that were the major political powers in the Tiers prior to the Overlord's conquest. Ruled by House Vendrien, the Realm of Apex was located in the center of the Tiers, between the nations of Azure and Haven, and just south of the Bastard Tier.

Apex fell in the year 429 TR after [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' armies successfully crushed the army of the [url=glossary:vendrien guard]Vendrien Guard[/url]. The survivors swore an oath of fealty to the Overlord in the Hall of Ascension, traditional throne room of the rulers of Apex.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>173</ID>
      <DefaultText>Haven</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>174</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Realm of Haven was one of the four major nations of the [url=glossary:younger realms]Younger Realms[/url] prior to the Overlord's conquest. The weakest of the four, Haven fell easily to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' armies early in the year 429 TR.

In the years after occupation, Haven became known for the large deposits of iron in its hills and rivers, making it the most strategically valuable locations in [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' empire.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>175</ID>
      <DefaultText>Azure</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>176</ID>
      <DefaultText>Its vast, fertile plains made Azure the largest of the [url=glossary:younger realms]Younger Realms[/url]. While nominally ruled by a Queen, the nation was in fact ruled by the many barons who owned the farmlands - as well as the people and Beasts who worked the fields.

Azure fell to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' armies in the year 431 TR, after the Archon [url=glossary:cairn]Cairn[/url] rebelled against the Overlord. [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] issued an [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] that shattered the land, destroying the rich farmlands with devastating earthquakes.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>177</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Tiers</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>178</ID>
      <DefaultText>A small peninsula in the northwest of Terratus, the Tiers are a backwater of civilization. The Tiers were the last corner of the world to submit to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' rule, and the Overlord's Archons are still establishing firm control over the people of this land.

The Tiers are named for the huge steps of land that lower in elevation from the northern peninsula that connects the Tiers to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Empire down to the ocean in the south.

The Tiers are strategically important to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] for two reasons. First, the Overlord's triremes must pass along the coast of the Tiers to connect the corners of the Empire. Before submitting to the Overlord, the School of Tides would often attack the Empire's merchant ships. Their command of the waves gave them a superior edge in naval battle. This was a major factor in the decision to attack by land, rather than by sea. The destruction of the School of Tides has freed the Overlord's ships to travel to all corners of the Empire.

Second, during the Conquest a large deposit of iron ore was found in the realm of Haven. This deposit is the largest yet discovered in [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Empire - since the Tanavon Mines were destroyed by the Overlord's [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url] in 428 TR.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>179</ID>
      <DefaultText>Contested Lands</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>180</ID>
      <DefaultText>Unofficially established in the second century of human civilization in the Tiers, the Contested Lands are a patch of mountains and forests that changed hands so many times as to become politically undesirable to all of its neighbors. During a particularly long stretch of peace, the Sages of the School of Ink and Quill built the [url=glossary:vellum citadel]Vellum Citadel[/url], and this has been the only permanent settlement in the Contested Lands to date.

As the School of Ink and Quill grew in prominence, the Contested Lands came under constant threat of invasion from the [url=glossary:younger realms]Younger Realms[/url], but a dangerous game of shifting alliances always assured that the [url=glossary:vellum citadel]Vellum Citadel[/url] never found itself in the middle of all-out war. This is likely due in no small part to the inhospitable nature of the land - and one's neighbors are less likely to invade if the grass is entirely browned, barren, and prone to blisteringly hot summers.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>181</ID>
      <DefaultText>Regents</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>182</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Regents of Stalwart were the traditional ruling body of the realm. The leader of the Regents Council was known as the First Regent, and traditionally led the [url=glossary:unbroken]Unbroken[/url] Blades into battle.

During [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' conquest of Stalwart, the Regents refused to surrender even when [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' armies presented terms that would preserve the lives of their people. For their selfishness, they were hunted down and slaughtered - all except for the last Regent, Straydus Herodin, who was trapped within Sentinel Stand Keep by the Overlord's [url=glossary:edict]Edict[/url].</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>183</ID>
      <DefaultText>Oldwalls</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>184</ID>
      <DefaultText>Constructed by the same civilization that built the Spires, the Oldwalls are massive stone walls that stretch across all of Terratus. Built from weathered stone, the Oldwalls tower above the land, visible for miles in every direction. Only the Spires reach taller than the Oldwalls.

By [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' law, the Oldwalls are forbidden.

Where there are Oldwalls, there are Bane. No one knows why the magical creatures are attracted to the Oldwalls, but every traveler who strays too near the walls is attacked. Very few who have attempted to enter the Oldwalls ever return alive.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>185</ID>
      <DefaultText>Bane</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>186</ID>
      <DefaultText>Very little is known about the Bane. They are savage, vicious creatures that attack humans and Beasts on sight. While normal humans can sometimes escape a Bane attack, they will pursue a mage or a Beast to the edges of Terratus.

Sages who have studied the Bane believe that they are creatures of magic. Whether they occur naturally or are created, no one knows. Some Sages speculate that the various forms of Bane are different stages of a life cycle, with the Bane becoming more complex and powerful as it ages.

No one knows why Bane are attracted to the Oldwalls, but everyone knows that travelling near those towering structures guarantees a Bane attack.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>187</ID>
      <DefaultText>Scourge</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>188</ID>
      <DefaultText>The most common - and aggressive - form of Bane is the Scourge. These vicious creatures travel in swarms, surrounding their prey with whirlwinds of tearing claws. Entire villages have been wiped out by a single pack of Scourge.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>189</ID>
      <DefaultText>Malice</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>190</ID>
      <DefaultText>Malice are rarely seen - at least, not by those who lived to tell of the encounter. A Malice's touch can drain and corrupt the living, taking their strength to empower the Bane.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>191</ID>
      <DefaultText>Wisp</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>192</ID>
      <DefaultText>Wisps are the weakest form of Bane, their form more diffuse than other types. Wisps are slow-moving, making them the easiest of the Bane to outrun. While a single Wisp can be defeated easily by a trained soldier, they are rarely found alone. Where a Wisp is found, the Scourge and Malice are not far behind.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>193</ID>
      <DefaultText>Havoc</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>194</ID>
      <DefaultText>Legends tell of an incredibly powerful form of Bane known only as the Havoc. There are no recorded sightings of a Havoc in recent centuries, so little is known of their abilities. 

Legends and campfire stories say that if a Havoc is seen, kill any other Bane present to deny the Havoc strength. No one knows why this advice has survived for centuries.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>195</ID>
      <DefaultText>Terratus</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>196</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] the Overlord is ruler of Terratus, the known world. The Overlord's Empire stretches from the Winter Sea in the east to the shores of the Tiers in the west.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>197</ID>
      <DefaultText>Terratus Grave</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>198</ID>
      <DefaultText>Terratus Grave is the larger of Terratus' two moons and is tide locked in orbit above [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Empire.

Its name comes from denizens of eastern Terratus, who see the moon as eternally looming on the western horizon; it is the grave behind which the sun descends each day.

Terratus Grave is of significant importance to the School of Tides, whose mages can harness this light into searing energy, or tap into the moon's pull on the ocean currents.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>199</ID>
      <DefaultText>Interloper</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>200</ID>
      <DefaultText>The smaller of Terratus' two moons, Interloper is a small, dense moon named for its speedy path across the sky. Orbiting the planet roughly three times per day, Interloper is of chief concern to those who travel the high seas. 

While Terratus Grave is the larger of the two moons, its gravitation is constant, whereas Interloper causes tidal shifts as it moves about its orbit.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>201</ID>
      <DefaultText>Fatebinder</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>202</ID>
      <DefaultText>A Fatebinder is a servant of [url=glossary:tunon]Tunon[/url] the Adjudicator, Archon of Justice. The Court of Fatebinders are the judges and executioners of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] law. Trained in legal lore as well as martial and magical prowess, Fatebinders have the task of enforcing [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Peace among the factions and Archons of the Overlord's Empire.

While the Overlord's rule is absolute, the Empire is too large for [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] to directly control everyone. Instead, [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] grants authority over different parts of the Empire to the Archons. Some Archons are governors of provinces or military districts, while others control important groups like armies, mage guilds, or specialized agents like the Fatebinders.

Each Archon is granted limited autonomy over their area of control. As long as they serve [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' goals and do not break any of the Overlord's laws, [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] permits the Archons to rule their armies and provinces in a manner of their choosing. Because of this, the Archons and the groups they control will often clash with one another. The Fatebinders were created by [url=glossary:tunon]Tunon[/url] to solve these problems.

A Fatebinder's duty is to resolve disputes that arise between the different armies and mage guilds - and sometimes between the Archons themselves.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>203</ID>
      <DefaultText>Northern Empire</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>204</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Northern Empire was the last great nation to fall before the armies of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] the Overlord. Led by Blood Echo, then Archon of War, the Overlord's armies expected the North to fall within a year. They did not count on the tactical brilliance of general [url=glossary:graven ashe]Graven Ashe[/url].

Outnumbered and cut off from supplies, the great general led his troops in a holding action that stymied all of Blood Echo's plans. It was during this desperate defense that [url=glossary:graven ashe]Graven Ashe[/url] began to manifest the abilities that would allow him to challenge Blood Echo for the mantle of Archon of War.

After defeating Blood Echo, [url=glossary:graven ashe]Graven Ashe[/url] was defeated by several of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' Archons and brought before the Overlord in chains. No one knows what [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url] said to the general that day, but Ashe emerged a loyal servant of the Overlord. With his surrender, the Northern legions bent knee to the Overlord as well, and the last great Empire of Terratus fell to [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]' rule.

The remnants of [url=glossary:graven ashe]Graven Ashe[/url]'s soldiers - those who survived the final battle with Blood Echo - became the core of his [url=glossary:disfavored]Disfavored[/url] legion.
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>206</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>208</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>210</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Ladies and Lords of the coastal realm of Haven are known to spend as much energy fighting each other as they do the other realms. In recent generations, many of the coastal cities rebelled and became known as the Free Cities, lawless dots along the coast. The majority of the realm’s political and economic might resided within them, and by the time of [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]’ conquest of the Tiers, all major coastal powers had declared independence. This left Haven with an ambiguous ruling structure that could not simultaneously weather political infighting and armed conflict, granting [url=glossary:kyros]Kyros[/url]’ forces an easy victory.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>211</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:stonestalkers]Stonestalkers[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>212</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:dps]DPS[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>213</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:dps]DPS[/url] stands for Damage Per Second. It divides the average damage a weapon will do on Hit (rather than on Graze or [url=glossary:crit]Crit[/url]) by the total recovery time of the character equipping the weapon.

The [url=glossary:dps]DPS[/url] calculation provides a quick way to compare general damage values of weapons, but does not take into account the relative damage types, accuracy bonuses, armor penetration values, or effects of attack skill on wielding the weapons being compared.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>214</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:disengagement defense]Disengagement Defense[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>215</ID>
      <DefaultText>Some abilities and items (such as boots) can grant bonuses to a character's defense against Disengagement attacks. 

When that character is engaged by an enemy and moves away, their [url=glossary:disengagement defense]Disengagement Defense[/url] provides a bonus to the defense type ([url=glossary:parry]Parry[/url], Endurance, etc.) they use to resist the enemy's Disengagement Attack. A high [url=glossary:disengagement defense]Disengagement Defense[/url] increases the chance for an enemy's attack to Graze or Miss.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>216</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] are powerful afflictions that last until a character rests. Each Wound reduces a character's maximum health.

[url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] can stack, adding their penalties together and making it hard for a character to continue through combat. When a character gains enough [url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url], the party should Rest and allow them to recover.

[url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] are gained when a character falls unconscious - when their [url=glossary:health]Health[/url] reaches zero during combat. On harder difficulty settings, [url=glossary:wounds]Wounds[/url] are also acquired when a character's health falls too low.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>217</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:chrysalis]Chrysalis[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>218</ID>
      <DefaultText>Small, parasitic insects with broad, brightly-colored wings, [url=glossary:chrysalis]Chrysalis[/url] often swarm in search of food. They use sharply hooked and hollow legs to affix themselves to their prey and feed. If left undisturbed, a female [url=glossary:chrysalis]Chrysalis[/url] excretes a quickly-hardening viscous substance from her abdomen, cocooning herself to her host before injecting her eggs into her victim's flesh.

While generally harmless to animals, [url=glossary:chrysalis]Chrysalis[/url] cause significant damage to homes and ships alike. Stories also warn of [url=glossary:chrysalis]Chrysalis[/url] swarms during times of famine: though they prefer plants, anecdotes claim that they will prey on animals when necessity requires.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>219</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:flightless]Flightless[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>220</ID>
      <DefaultText>A breed of ornery, dun-colored birds common throughout the Tiers, [url=glossary:flightless]flightless[/url] serve as a staple of hunters' diets. Due to their aggressive temperament and the gamey tastelessness of their meat, they have never proven popular among farmers.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>224</ID>
      <DefaultText>This choice betrays your allies, turning them against you. You will abandon your current faction-based quests and instead forge an independent path through the Tiers.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>225</ID>
      <DefaultText>[url=glossary:betray alliance]Betray Alliance[/url]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>226</ID>
      <DefaultText>Increases amount of incoming damage for a medium duration</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>227</ID>
      <DefaultText>Shadow's Treachery</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
  </Entries>
